ks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lincolnshire): habitational name from either of two places called Holtby in North Yorkshire, from the Old Norse personal name <i>Holti</i> + Old Norse <i>bȳ</i> ‘farmstead, village’."],"variants":[{"name":"Holby","meanings":["English (Essex): apparently a habitational name, possibly a variant of   Holtby  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Holtby was born in 1160, in Sessay, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1160–":"1160–Surnud","1296–1374":"1296–1374","1160–Male":"1160–Surnud","1374":"1374","1296":"1296","1160":"1160","Sessay, Yorkshire, England":"Sessay, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1160–":"1160–Kuollut","1296–1374":"1296–1374","1160–Male":"1160–Kuollut","1374":"1374","1296":"1296","1160":"1160","Sessay, Yorkshire, England":"Sessay, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1160–":"1160–Décédé","1296–1374":"1296–1374","1160–Male":"1160–Décédé","1374":"1374","1296":"1296","1160":"1160","Sessay, Yorkshire, England":"Sessay, Everwyck, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"William Holtby est né en 1160, à Sessay, Everwyck, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Il a eu au moins 1 fille."},"de":{"1160–":"1160–